00:39:34.172 --> 00:39:38.910 align:middle line:84%
or any other way and they
couldn't fake the dogs out.

00:39:38.910 --> 00:39:40.611 align:middle line:90%
The dogs knew.

00:39:40.611 --> 00:39:44.449 align:middle line:84%
This looks like what
Sheldrake call morphic fields

00:39:44.449 --> 00:39:47.552 align:middle line:84%
which go beyond spatial
separation.

00:39:47.552 --> 00:39:52.356 align:middle line:84%
This is what we're calling
the one mind hypothesis.

00:39:52.356 --> 00:39:55.593 align:middle line:84%
I'm happy to say that
Sheldrake came to my home

00:39:55.593 --> 00:40:00.364 align:middle line:84%
when his book was in
manuscript phase and we talked

00:40:00.364 --> 00:40:03.234 align:middle line:84%
about these things and we
have a great time doing it

00:40:03.234 --> 00:40:04.669 align:middle line:84%
because we were on the
same channel about it.

00:40:04.669 --> 00:40:08.072 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Well-- he is
a wonderful gentleman.

00:40:08.072 --> 00:40:09.507 align:middle line:90%
I have great respect for.

00:40:09.507 --> 00:40:11.642 align:middle line:90%
He's actually I've heard myself

00:40:11.642 --> 00:40:14.178 align:middle line:84%
and others also just
to bring this up.

00:40:14.178 --> 00:40:16.247 align:middle line:90%
I have misused the terminology

00:40:16.247 --> 00:40:18.249 align:middle line:84%
and called it morphogenic
fields.

00:40:18.249 --> 00:40:21.385 align:middle line:84%
And I was in his home in
London one time and he said no,

00:40:21.385 --> 00:40:24.055 align:middle line:90%
no it is not morphogenic and--

00:40:24.055 --> 00:40:26.224 align:middle line:84%
now I hear with other people
he said its either more

00:40:26.224 --> 00:40:28.226 align:middle line:84%
morphogenetic or
more morphic fields.

00:40:28.226 --> 00:40:30.728 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just setting that
straight for all of us.

00:40:30.728 --> 00:40:31.295 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: No.

00:40:31.295 --> 00:40:32.296 align:middle line:90%
Good for you.

00:40:32.296 --> 00:40:35.633 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: And so
I wanted to talk--

00:40:35.633 --> 00:40:41.239 align:middle line:84%
moving from the humans and
the morphic fields of mind

00:40:41.239 --> 00:40:43.508 align:middle line:84%
into what happens
even beyond death.

00:40:43.508 --> 00:40:47.278 align:middle line:84%
Because one thing we know for
sure is what ever memory is,

00:40:47.278 --> 00:40:51.449 align:middle line:84%
what ever mind is, is not
inside this obviously.

00:40:51.449 --> 00:40:53.518 align:middle line:84%
This may be simply
or processing unit

00:40:53.518 --> 00:40:56.387 align:middle line:84%
to access it were I think
scientist is becoming pretty

00:40:56.387 --> 00:40:57.288 align:middle line:90%
clear on that.

00:40:57.288 --> 00:40:58.689 align:middle line:90%
So let's talk about what happens

00:40:58.689 --> 00:41:00.791 align:middle line:84%
after death you have
some interesting things

00:41:00.791 --> 00:41:03.394 align:middle line:90%
about near death experiences.

00:41:03.394 --> 00:41:05.696 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Well-- only
15 million Americans

00:41:05.696 --> 00:41:08.666 align:middle line:84%
by now have had what we call
a near death experience.

00:41:08.666 --> 00:41:11.068 align:middle line:84%
And one thing that they
come back and tell us is

00:41:11.068 --> 00:41:13.104 align:middle line:90%
that we're not separate.

00:41:13.104 --> 00:41:14.605 align:middle line:90%
We're all united.

00:41:14.605 --> 00:41:15.973 align:middle line:90%
There's no disunity.

00:41:15.973 --> 00:41:20.344 align:middle line:84%
Everything is at that dimension
one and that sense of unity

00:41:20.344 --> 00:41:22.346 align:middle line:84%
and connectedness
is also marinated

00:41:22.346 --> 00:41:24.949 align:middle line:90%
in this intense felling of love.

00:41:24.949 --> 00:41:27.919 align:middle line:84%
That's the classic
near death experience

00:41:27.919 --> 00:41:31.489 align:middle line:84%
which so many people have
return to tell us about.

00:41:31.489 --> 00:41:35.860 align:middle line:84%
This is I think indirect
evidence of immortality

00:41:35.860 --> 00:41:38.563 align:middle line:84%
but comment immortality
and eternality

00:41:38.563 --> 00:41:40.364 align:middle line:90%
in slightly different way.

00:41:40.364 --> 00:41:43.701 align:middle line:84%
The way I think we can
understand it is to say

00:41:43.701 --> 00:41:47.138 align:middle line:84%
that the one mind
is the dimension

00:41:47.138 --> 00:41:52.109 align:middle line:84%
where individual minds gather
and it's beyond space and time.

00:41:52.109 --> 00:41:55.580 align:middle line:84%
The operative word
for me is non-local.

00:41:55.580 --> 00:41:58.482 align:middle line:84%
That's just a fancy
word for infinite.

00:41:58.482 --> 00:42:02.753 align:middle line:84%
Now something is infinite
in time, it's immortal.

00:42:02.753 --> 00:42:06.357 align:middle line:84%
So to say that our minds behave
as if they're infinite in time

00:42:06.357 --> 00:42:14.332 align:middle line:84%
and non-local mandates
immortality, it just arises.

00:42:14.332 --> 00:42:18.669 align:middle line:84%
As matter of fact you can't
be partially non-local.

00:42:18.669 --> 00:42:21.973 align:middle line:84%
Non-locality involves
infinitude.

00:42:21.973 --> 00:42:23.541 align:middle line:90%
So, it's like being pregnant.

00:42:23.541 --> 00:42:25.276 align:middle line:84%
You can't be a little
bit pregnant

00:42:25.276 --> 00:42:27.478 align:middle line:84%
and either can you be
a little non-local.

00:42:27.478 --> 00:42:29.780 align:middle line:84%
So the fact there, our
minds behave non-locally

00:42:29.780 --> 00:42:34.685 align:middle line:84%
and this existence is solid
evidence that something

00:42:34.685 --> 00:42:36.554 align:middle line:84%
about our minds has
to be infinite

00:42:36.554 --> 00:42:39.323 align:middle line:84%
in space therefore
immortal and internal.

00:42:39.323 --> 00:42:44.061 align:middle line:84%
So I think when you put people's
near death experiences together

00:42:44.061 --> 00:42:48.532 align:middle line:84%
with the experiments which
show it is non-local quality

00:42:48.532 --> 00:42:49.834 align:middle line:90%
of conscious thing,

00:42:49.834 --> 00:42:51.836 align:middle line:84%
you've really got something
powerful here that points

00:42:51.836 --> 00:42:54.505 align:middle line:84%
like an arrow toward
immortality.

00:42:54.505 --> 00:42:55.740 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Absolutely.

00:42:55.740 --> 00:42:57.408 align:middle line:84%
And one thing people
don't normally talk

00:42:57.408 --> 00:43:00.211 align:middle line:84%
about in their books is the
shared death experience,

00:43:00.211 --> 00:43:02.146 align:middle line:84%
that's the nuance
of that but explain

00:43:02.146 --> 00:43:04.348 align:middle line:84%
to us what a shared
death experience is?

00:43:04.348 --> 00:43:07.084 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Well this has
come to light through cases

00:43:07.084 --> 00:43:09.020 align:middle line:84%
that been collected
but Dr. Raymond Moody

00:43:09.020 --> 00:43:14.925 align:middle line:84%
who gave us this 1970's book,
Got A life, the Beyond Life.

00:43:14.925 --> 00:43:18.729 align:middle line:84%
And so a shared death
experience is the experience

00:43:18.729 --> 00:43:20.765 align:middle line:90%
like a near death experience

00:43:20.765 --> 00:43:23.801 align:middle line:84%
without going through--
without nearly dying.

00:43:23.801 --> 00:43:26.937 align:middle line:84%
And so for example people can
be gathered around a bedside

00:43:26.937 --> 00:43:29.206 align:middle line:90%
of a loved one who is dying

00:43:29.206 --> 00:43:32.743 align:middle line:84%
and that loved one maybe
having a near death experience

00:43:32.743 --> 00:43:35.012 align:middle line:90%
but it's like that's catching.

00:43:35.012 --> 00:43:39.050 align:middle line:84%
The people around the
bedside begin to share it

00:43:39.050 --> 00:43:42.119 align:middle line:84%
and they have these
transcending experiences

00:43:42.119 --> 00:43:46.791 align:middle line:84%
and come back after-- after they
gone through them and tell us,

00:43:46.791 --> 00:43:49.293 align:middle line:84%
what's the dead ringer for
a near death experience?

00:43:49.293 --> 00:43:52.596 align:middle line:84%
What it say is that people
do not have to nearly die

00:43:52.596 --> 00:43:55.232 align:middle line:84%
in order have near
death like experience.

00:43:55.232 --> 00:43:58.202 align:middle line:84%
You can just have
it because you care

00:43:58.202 --> 00:44:00.004 align:middle line:84%
about the person
who's having it--

00:44:00.004 --> 00:44:02.239 align:middle line:84%
here's that love
connection again.

00:44:02.239 --> 00:44:04.241 align:middle line:84%
This feeling of compassion
of caring

00:44:04.241 --> 00:44:07.111 align:middle line:84%
about someone who's your
mother, your father,

00:44:07.111 --> 00:44:10.948 align:middle line:84%
your child who is dying
is enough to catapult you

00:44:10.948 --> 00:44:12.850 align:middle line:90%
into the actual experience.

00:44:12.850 --> 00:44:14.485 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: And I can
go forward or backward?

00:44:14.485 --> 00:44:16.020 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Yes, it
certainly can.

00:44:16.020 --> 00:44:19.824 align:middle line:84%
Moody says that these
are probably as common

00:44:19.824 --> 00:44:22.259 align:middle line:90%
as the near death experience.

00:44:22.259 --> 00:44:26.497 align:middle line:84%
But people don't really want to
talk about them in the same way

00:44:26.497 --> 00:44:29.133 align:middle line:84%
that people never wanted to talk
about the near death experience

00:44:29.133 --> 00:44:30.968 align:middle line:90%
until Moody wrote about it.

00:44:30.968 --> 00:44:34.071 align:middle line:84%
I predict that we're
going to see, just a flood

00:44:34.071 --> 00:44:37.408 align:middle line:84%
of shared death experiences
arising in our culture

00:44:37.408 --> 00:44:40.377 align:middle line:84%
that people will talk about when
they become more comfortable

00:44:40.377 --> 00:44:41.746 align:middle line:90%
with the idea.

00:44:41.746 --> 00:44:44.715 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Yes, when they feel
there's permission to do so.

00:44:44.715 --> 00:44:45.716 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Yes.

00:44:45.716 --> 00:44:48.652 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: This reminds
me of going back

00:44:48.652 --> 00:44:50.387 align:middle line:90%
as far as much forward.

00:44:50.387 --> 00:44:53.557 align:middle line:84%
Years ago I love the
subject of hypnotherapy

00:44:53.557 --> 00:44:57.428 align:middle line:84%
and so I studied for-- well, you
know, it's usually a few months

00:44:57.428 --> 00:45:00.664 align:middle line:84%
and a few nights a week, you got
your certification but I find

00:45:00.664 --> 00:45:02.566 align:middle line:84%
that I already had a resonance
with it and could do it.

00:45:02.566 --> 00:45:05.736 align:middle line:84%
I didn't need the certification
or anything to do that.

00:45:05.736 --> 00:45:09.540 align:middle line:84%
And I would-- I really enjoyed
taking people into the past

00:45:09.540 --> 00:45:13.444 align:middle line:84%
and into future particularly
more so that any clinical stuff.

00:45:13.444 --> 00:45:18.649 align:middle line:84%
And one thing I found was that
it was not unusual once you were

00:45:18.649 --> 00:45:23.854 align:middle line:84%
in this guiding this person to
go where they needed to go to be

00:45:23.854 --> 00:45:28.559 align:middle line:84%
in their mind with them to see
the-- see the scene and be there

00:45:28.559 --> 00:45:31.061 align:middle line:84%
and fill it before
they would explain it.

00:45:31.061 --> 00:45:34.832 align:middle line:84%
And by the same token I
found that in that period

00:45:34.832 --> 00:45:39.170 align:middle line:84%
of time it became easy to access
people in their consciousness

00:45:39.170 --> 00:45:42.473 align:middle line:84%
and memories within the
days before their birth

00:45:42.473 --> 00:45:44.508 align:middle line:84%
and within the days
after their death.

00:45:44.508 --> 00:45:47.044 align:middle line:84%
And they could tell me
things that would turn out.

00:45:47.044 --> 00:45:48.245 align:middle line:90%
Where is the money Fred?

00:45:48.245 --> 00:45:48.946 align:middle line:90%
Where did you hide it?

00:45:48.946 --> 00:45:50.147 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: that's right.

00:45:50.147 --> 00:45:50.714 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: You know and
they tell you where it is.

00:45:50.714 --> 00:45:52.116 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Yeah.

00:45:52.116 --> 00:45:53.751 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: So this is something
that was really quite easy to do

00:45:53.751 --> 00:45:55.386 align:middle line:90%
and that anybody can do.

00:45:55.386 --> 00:45:56.787 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Yes.

00:45:56.787 --> 00:45:59.356 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: So there is no time
space boundary whether it's the

00:45:59.356 --> 00:46:01.158 align:middle line:90%
past present or future.

00:46:01.158 --> 00:46:03.527 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: You know that's a
hard lesson for humans to come

00:46:03.527 --> 00:46:05.563 align:middle line:90%
to grips with this idea

00:46:05.563 --> 00:46:08.499 align:middle line:84%
that time could flow
backwards carrying information

00:46:08.499 --> 00:46:12.002 align:middle line:84%
from the future into the present
which you might experience

00:46:12.002 --> 00:46:14.371 align:middle line:90%
as pre-cognition or premunition.

00:46:14.371 --> 00:46:20.044 align:middle line:84%
And I think that hypnosis gives
some profound insight into that.

00:46:20.044 --> 00:46:20.811 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yes.

00:46:20.811 --> 00:46:21.812 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Also dreams do.

00:46:21.812 --> 00:46:22.880 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Dreams, yes.

00:46:22.880 --> 00:46:24.248 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: You know
when we're dreaming,

00:46:24.248 --> 00:46:29.119 align:middle line:84%
we don't erect these barriers
of logic which we experience

00:46:29.119 --> 00:46:31.522 align:middle line:84%
when we're awake which
saying this is nonsense.

00:46:31.522 --> 00:46:33.624 align:middle line:84%
This is impossible,
this couldn't happen.

00:46:33.624 --> 00:46:35.459 align:middle line:90%
In dreams, it's OK.

00:46:35.459 --> 00:46:36.694 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yes, OK.

00:46:36.694 --> 00:46:38.395 align:middle line:90%
Let's talk-- now we talk little

00:46:38.395 --> 00:46:44.568 align:middle line:84%
about how animals have this pure
guile state where they can sense

00:46:44.568 --> 00:46:49.039 align:middle line:84%
where need is or they can
sense to follow where love is.

00:46:49.039 --> 00:46:52.576 align:middle line:84%
But the same existed for
us before we squashed it.

00:46:52.576 --> 00:46:53.511 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Yes.

00:46:53.511 --> 00:46:55.145 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: And one
of the stories

00:46:55.145 --> 00:46:56.981 align:middle line:84%
in your book I just
love has to do

00:46:56.981 --> 00:47:00.084 align:middle line:90%
with aboriginal smoke signals.

00:47:00.084 --> 00:47:02.086 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about these
phenomena 'cause it's

00:47:02.086 --> 00:47:03.654 align:middle line:90%
completely misunderstood.

00:47:03.654 --> 00:47:04.989 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Oh absolutely.

00:47:04.989 --> 00:47:07.157 align:middle line:84%
There's quite a literature
about this.

00:47:07.157 --> 00:47:09.627 align:middle line:84%
A lot of it has to do
with not Native Americans

00:47:09.627 --> 00:47:10.828 align:middle line:90%
but native Australians.

00:47:10.828 --> 00:47:12.329 align:middle line:90%
They have aborigines.

00:47:12.329 --> 00:47:17.167 align:middle line:84%
And extensive work has been done
interviewing Native Americans.

00:47:17.167 --> 00:47:21.572 align:middle line:84%
This was usually done in
the early part of the 1900s

00:47:21.572 --> 00:47:25.609 align:middle line:84%
when not a lot was known
about aboriginal culture.

00:47:25.609 --> 00:47:28.913 align:middle line:84%
In any case White people
almost always believed

00:47:28.913 --> 00:47:33.817 align:middle line:84%
that there was some
code that was involved

00:47:33.817 --> 00:47:38.422 align:middle line:84%
with that smoke signals like,
you know, one puff is come here.

00:47:38.422 --> 00:47:39.623 align:middle line:90%
Two puffs I'll meet you there.

00:47:39.623 --> 00:47:41.091 align:middle line:90%
Something like they set--

00:47:41.091 --> 00:47:42.793 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Like Morse
code of some kind.

00:47:42.793 --> 00:47:46.130 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Yes, like-- but the
aborigines continually insisted

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:49.066 align:middle line:84%
that it was just an
attention getting device.

00:47:49.066 --> 00:47:54.305 align:middle line:84%
It was a way of alerting someone
who was out there, listen up.

00:47:54.305 --> 00:47:55.306 align:middle line:90%
Pay attention.

00:47:55.306 --> 00:47:57.574 align:middle line:84%
I have something I
want to tell you.

00:47:57.574 --> 00:48:02.513 align:middle line:84%
And the communication would go
not through the puffs of smoke

00:48:02.513 --> 00:48:05.382 align:middle line:84%
but through actual sending
of thoughts from one person

00:48:05.382 --> 00:48:07.251 align:middle line:90%
to another at a distance.

00:48:07.251 --> 00:48:13.791 align:middle line:84%
This is what we call telepathy
in-- in consciousness research.

00:48:13.791 --> 00:48:17.261 align:middle line:84%
But it's a hard lesson
for White folks to learn.

00:48:17.261 --> 00:48:17.895 align:middle line:90%
I mean, you know, time--

00:48:17.895 --> 00:48:19.263 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: It is.

00:48:19.263 --> 00:48:20.798 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: White
folk pioneers just never really

00:48:20.798 --> 00:48:21.899 align:middle line:90%
got it.

00:48:21.899 --> 00:48:25.336 align:middle line:84%
And it's an example I
think of the ability

00:48:25.336 --> 00:48:28.605 align:middle line:84%
of primitive pre-modern
cultures to accept this idea

00:48:28.605 --> 00:48:31.241 align:middle line:84%
of one minded communication
almost naturally.

00:48:31.241 --> 00:48:34.044 align:middle line:90%
They didn't struggle with it.

00:48:34.044 --> 00:48:35.946 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: There's
another story you had--

00:48:35.946 --> 00:48:37.381 align:middle line:84%
we have several things
to get through.

00:48:37.381 --> 00:48:39.516 align:middle line:84%
I want to get to the twins
'cause I love this part.

00:48:39.516 --> 00:48:42.419 align:middle line:84%
But just really briefly I don't
how you pronounce his name

00:48:42.419 --> 00:48:43.554 align:middle line:90%
whether it was Ikan

00:48:43.554 --> 00:48:46.724 align:middle line:90%
or Ikan the blind guide.

00:48:46.724 --> 00:48:50.961 align:middle line:84%
This is a fabulous story because
he was able to connect not just

00:48:50.961 --> 00:48:53.864 align:middle line:84%
with each other but through the
eyes of people who could see

00:48:53.864 --> 00:48:55.666 align:middle line:84%
and through the earth
speaking to him.

00:48:55.666 --> 00:48:59.069 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Right, well this
is from the work of Gershan--

00:48:59.069 --> 00:49:03.874 align:middle line:84%
Douchan Gersi who was an
explorer, an adventurer

00:49:03.874 --> 00:49:06.543 align:middle line:90%
and a film maker who drove one--

00:49:06.543 --> 00:49:10.914 align:middle line:84%
on one occasion from North
Africa down to Timbuktu

00:49:10.914 --> 00:49:14.818 align:middle line:84%
which is several hundred miles
away across trackless waste.

00:49:14.818 --> 00:49:17.454 align:middle line:84%
He went-- before he started his
trip to a military commander

00:49:17.454 --> 00:49:20.858 align:middle line:84%
at the post and he said,
"Furnish me the guide.

00:49:20.858 --> 00:49:22.693 align:middle line:84%
I've got to have
an expert guide."

00:49:22.693 --> 00:49:26.597 align:middle line:84%
So he sends in ICAN and he says
oh there's one little problem

00:49:26.597 --> 00:49:27.698 align:middle line:90%
he's blind.

00:49:27.698 --> 00:49:28.999 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: That instills
confidence.

00:49:28.999 --> 00:49:30.601 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: He can't see.

00:49:30.601 --> 00:49:33.337 align:middle line:84%
So but he said he'll
get you there.

00:49:33.337 --> 00:49:34.672 align:middle line:90%
He's perfect.

00:49:34.672 --> 00:49:37.174 align:middle line:84%
Well this didn't make any sense
to Gersi but he went along

00:49:37.174 --> 00:49:41.612 align:middle line:84%
with it and as it turned out
this guy used other people minds

00:49:41.612 --> 00:49:45.616 align:middle line:84%
and vision to tell
him where to go.

00:49:45.616 --> 00:49:48.318 align:middle line:84%
And so Ikan would
tell Gersi and a set

00:49:48.318 --> 00:49:53.657 align:middle line:84%
of companions don't talk just
look around and just be quiet

00:49:53.657 --> 00:49:55.325 align:middle line:90%
and just witness things.

00:49:55.325 --> 00:49:57.828 align:middle line:84%
And so it was that he
could see through the eyes

00:49:57.828 --> 00:50:01.065 align:middle line:84%
and the consciousness
of the sided people.

00:50:01.065 --> 00:50:06.170 align:middle line:84%
And he got them there without
any hesitation or delay at all.

00:50:06.170 --> 00:50:09.339 align:middle line:84%
And he will also just simply
go out and sit in the desert

00:50:09.339 --> 00:50:13.477 align:middle line:84%
and smell things and sort of
just sense whatever he sense.

00:50:13.477 --> 00:50:15.145 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Where water was.

00:50:15.145 --> 00:50:16.880 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: He was-- where
water was and it was

00:50:16.880 --> 00:50:21.919 align:middle line:84%
as if he was one big
human sensing machine.

00:50:21.919 --> 00:50:24.021 align:middle line:90%
And vision was only part of it.

00:50:24.021 --> 00:50:26.457 align:middle line:84%
I mean and he could do without
the vision because he was

00:50:26.457 --> 00:50:28.859 align:middle line:84%
so tuned in with
everything else.

00:50:28.859 --> 00:50:30.360 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Larry do you
think that's something

00:50:30.360 --> 00:50:32.129 align:middle line:84%
that any human being
if they choose

00:50:32.129 --> 00:50:34.431 align:middle line:90%
to can be trained back into?

00:50:34.431 --> 00:50:35.833 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: I think so.

00:50:35.833 --> 00:50:38.702 align:middle line:84%
When I was in Vietnam I saw this
all the time in kids who were

00:50:38.702 --> 00:50:42.339 align:middle line:84%
out on patrols, who simply knew
where to stay up and not to stay

00:50:42.339 --> 00:50:44.675 align:middle line:84%
up and where a sniper
was and whatnot.

00:50:44.675 --> 00:50:47.811 align:middle line:84%
This was a survival
oriented capacity.

00:50:47.811 --> 00:50:49.580 align:middle line:84%
Some of these kids,
you know, none of them

00:50:49.580 --> 00:50:51.281 align:middle line:84%
where into consciousness
nature research.

00:50:51.281 --> 00:50:52.082 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Right.

00:50:52.082 --> 00:50:52.916 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: They didn't care.

00:50:52.916 --> 00:50:54.284 align:middle line:90%
They just wanted to stay alive.

00:50:54.284 --> 00:50:57.955 align:middle line:84%
And I'll never forget when one
of them told me once, "Doc,

00:50:57.955 --> 00:51:01.091 align:middle line:84%
you don't need to know
a long time ahead."

00:51:01.091 --> 00:51:03.460 align:middle line:84%
He says, "Sometimes
only a second

00:51:03.460 --> 00:51:06.363 align:middle line:84%
or two is enough
to save your life."

00:51:06.363 --> 00:51:08.765 align:middle line:84%
And many of these
young men would say

00:51:08.765 --> 00:51:11.802 align:middle line:84%
that they have some sense
that they can't explain.

00:51:11.802 --> 00:51:14.304 align:middle line:84%
That is reason they're
still alive.

00:51:14.304 --> 00:51:18.175 align:middle line:84%
You see this in every situation
where people's lives are

00:51:18.175 --> 00:51:20.711 align:middle line:90%
at stake such as in combat.

00:51:20.711 --> 00:51:21.712 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Absolutely.

00:51:21.712 --> 00:51:23.547 align:middle line:84%
Now we get to the
subject of twins.

00:51:23.547 --> 00:51:24.948 align:middle line:90%
You're a twin.

00:51:24.948 --> 00:51:27.417 align:middle line:84%
Did I read correctly, your
wife-- is your wife a twin?

00:51:27.417 --> 00:51:28.519 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Yes.

00:51:28.519 --> 00:51:29.620 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: You're a
twin, your wife is twin.

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:31.021 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Yes, it
kinds of strange.

00:51:31.021 --> 00:51:34.491 align:middle line:84%
Our household has been sort of
a laboratory for strange, weird,

00:51:34.491 --> 00:51:36.894 align:middle line:84%
twin stuff for quite
a long time.

00:51:36.894 --> 00:51:38.228 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Well and you read

00:51:38.228 --> 00:51:40.397 align:middle line:84%
about some other strange twin
stuff where you're talking

00:51:40.397 --> 00:51:44.568 align:middle line:84%
about essentially, it's almost
like one being, one mind,

00:51:44.568 --> 00:51:48.071 align:middle line:84%
one being is occupying two
separate bodies completely.

00:51:48.071 --> 00:51:50.407 align:middle line:90%
Let's talk about the Twin Jims.

00:51:50.407 --> 00:51:52.543 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Well the
Twin Jims were part

00:51:52.543 --> 00:51:55.245 align:middle line:84%
of the Minnesota
Twin Study Program.

00:51:55.245 --> 00:51:59.416 align:middle line:84%
And they came together
late in life

00:51:59.416 --> 00:52:03.020 align:middle line:84%
after having been separated
shortly after birth and raised

00:52:03.020 --> 00:52:06.323 align:middle line:84%
in different homes and
different environments but later

00:52:06.323 --> 00:52:09.660 align:middle line:84%
in their 40s when they
came together they found

00:52:09.660 --> 00:52:12.896 align:middle line:84%
out that they had lived
almost identical lives.

00:52:12.896 --> 00:52:15.365 align:middle line:84%
They married women
of the same name.

00:52:15.365 --> 00:52:18.468 align:middle line:84%
They named their first
born son as the same name.

00:52:18.468 --> 00:52:21.238 align:middle line:84%
They had a dog they
named the same thing.

00:52:21.238 --> 00:52:25.209 align:middle line:84%
They had vacationed at the
same area on the Gulf Cost

00:52:25.209 --> 00:52:29.346 align:middle line:84%
about just a few blocks from
one another not knowing it.

00:52:29.346 --> 00:52:32.583 align:middle line:84%
Anybody looking at this
stuff would say this is

00:52:32.583 --> 00:52:33.684 align:middle line:90%
absolutely weird.

00:52:33.684 --> 00:52:35.586 align:middle line:90%
How do you explain this?

00:52:35.586 --> 00:52:40.657 align:middle line:84%
Well the researcher said
this is all genetic stuff.

00:52:40.657 --> 00:52:42.793 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
just too easy on answer

00:52:42.793 --> 00:52:48.098 align:middle line:84%
because nobody has a clue
about how genes would code

00:52:48.098 --> 00:52:52.135 align:middle line:84%
in two different individuals
with respect to wives

00:52:52.135 --> 00:52:54.638 align:middle line:84%
who are named the same,
children who are named the same.

00:52:54.638 --> 00:52:56.206 align:middle line:90%
Dogs who are named the same.

00:52:56.206 --> 00:52:57.507 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Similar
personalities,

00:52:57.507 --> 00:53:00.544 align:middle line:84%
virtually identical
ticks and propensities.

00:53:00.544 --> 00:53:01.979 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: It could be.

00:53:01.979 --> 00:53:03.380 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:53:03.380 --> 00:53:06.183 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Actually, but there's
an associated body of evidence

00:53:06.183 --> 00:53:10.053 align:middle line:84%
which makes me very dubious
about a genetic explanation--

00:53:10.053 --> 00:53:10.988 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Absolutely.

00:53:10.988 --> 00:53:11.655 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: -- for
all these stuff.

00:53:11.655 --> 00:53:12.656 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: There has

00:53:12.656 --> 00:53:13.991 align:middle line:84%
to be something greater
in effect there.

00:53:13.991 --> 00:53:16.893 align:middle line:84%
And when they finally met
each other they fell in love.

00:53:16.893 --> 00:53:18.095 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: They did.

00:53:18.095 --> 00:53:20.897 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: For the first
time they knew themselves.

00:53:20.897 --> 00:53:21.999 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Well they felt

00:53:21.999 --> 00:53:23.500 align:middle line:84%
as if their whole life
had been transformed

00:53:23.500 --> 00:53:25.269 align:middle line:90%
by this reconnection.

00:53:25.269 --> 00:53:28.906 align:middle line:84%
And this gets back to what
were talking about earlier

00:53:28.906 --> 00:53:32.876 align:middle line:84%
about perhaps the
thread of compassion

00:53:32.876 --> 00:53:36.013 align:middle line:84%
and love was the thing that
helped their minds unit

00:53:36.013 --> 00:53:39.516 align:middle line:84%
and prepare them for
these identical behaviors.

00:53:39.516 --> 00:53:41.818 align:middle line:90%
Can I mention one other example?

00:53:41.818 --> 00:53:42.753 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yes, absolutely.

00:53:42.753 --> 00:53:44.321 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: That supports
this idea.

00:53:44.321 --> 00:53:46.523 align:middle line:84%
This had to do with
identical twin girls

00:53:46.523 --> 00:53:50.227 align:middle line:84%
who were four years old
in Spain in the 1970s

00:53:50.227 --> 00:53:51.261 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Is this
Sylvia and Martha?

00:53:51.261 --> 00:53:52.596 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: This is
Sylvia and Martha.

00:53:52.596 --> 00:53:53.864 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: That's
what I was going

00:53:53.864 --> 00:53:55.098 align:middle line:90%
to bring up and I so love it.

00:53:55.098 --> 00:53:55.766 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: That s right.

00:53:55.766 --> 00:53:56.967 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:53:56.967 --> 00:53:57.668 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: Well we're the
same-- same mind here.

00:53:57.668 --> 00:53:59.002 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Here we are.

00:53:59.002 --> 00:54:00.737 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: So the father took
Sylvia, this four little--

00:54:00.737 --> 00:54:03.473 align:middle line:84%
four year old girl, off
to visit the grandparents

00:54:03.473 --> 00:54:06.276 align:middle line:84%
who were ten miles--
tens of miles away.

00:54:06.276 --> 00:54:09.780 align:middle line:84%
Martha stayed home to help
her mom with household chores.

00:54:09.780 --> 00:54:13.617 align:middle line:84%
Unfortunately, Martha touched
a red hot iron and erupted

00:54:13.617 --> 00:54:16.420 align:middle line:90%
with a large second degree burn,

00:54:16.420 --> 00:54:19.890 align:middle line:84%
a huge blister on
her right hand.

00:54:19.890 --> 00:54:22.959 align:middle line:84%
At the same time it
was determined tens

00:54:22.959 --> 00:54:26.163 align:middle line:84%
of miles away her
twin sister erupted

00:54:26.163 --> 00:54:30.867 align:middle line:84%
with an identical blister on the
same hand and the same pattern.

00:54:30.867 --> 00:54:32.669 align:middle line:84%
I don't see how you
get that out of genes.

00:54:32.669 --> 00:54:33.770 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Exactly.

00:54:33.770 --> 00:54:35.005 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: I mean I just
don't think that's a

00:54:35.005 --> 00:54:36.640 align:middle line:90%
proper explanation.

00:54:36.640 --> 00:54:41.978 align:middle line:84%
Something else is going on that
unites people at a distance.

00:54:41.978 --> 00:54:44.915 align:middle line:84%
You see it in full
volume in identical twins

00:54:44.915 --> 00:54:47.317 align:middle line:84%
who had a heart connection
with one another.

00:54:47.317 --> 00:54:50.053 align:middle line:84%
But you see it in other people
who were fundamentally bonded

00:54:50.053 --> 00:54:57.761 align:middle line:84%
like a mother and a child or
lovers or siblings and so on.

00:54:57.761 --> 00:54:59.463 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Yeah, this
is just to the extreme.

00:54:59.463 --> 00:55:02.232 align:middle line:84%
And again that could bring up
a lot of others spooky kinds

00:55:02.232 --> 00:55:05.836 align:middle line:84%
of subjects like maybe living
literally, an entity living

00:55:05.836 --> 00:55:08.572 align:middle line:84%
in two realities at the
same times simultaneously

00:55:08.572 --> 00:55:09.906 align:middle line:90%
or any number of things.

00:55:09.906 --> 00:55:12.209 align:middle line:84%
But the point is that it all
goes back to non-local mind.

00:55:12.209 --> 00:55:13.510 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: I believe it does.

00:55:13.510 --> 00:55:15.979 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: And now we only
have about five minutes left

00:55:15.979 --> 00:55:20.550 align:middle line:84%
and I wanted to get into
more the instructional part

00:55:20.550 --> 00:55:24.287 align:middle line:84%
about how we access this because
there are two keywords here

00:55:24.287 --> 00:55:25.756 align:middle line:84%
and I'd like you
to expand on it.

00:55:25.756 --> 00:55:28.892 align:middle line:84%
And one has to do
with creativity,

00:55:28.892 --> 00:55:30.794 align:middle line:90%
the field of creation.

00:55:30.794 --> 00:55:33.263 align:middle line:84%
And of course the
final one is love.

00:55:33.263 --> 00:55:34.831 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Yes.

00:55:34.831 --> 00:55:37.567 align:middle line:84%
Well I think for
starters, it's a mistake

00:55:37.567 --> 00:55:40.971 align:middle line:90%
to try too hard to access it.

00:55:40.971 --> 00:55:43.473 align:middle line:84%
You know, all that's actually
said there is something he

00:55:43.473 --> 00:55:47.244 align:middle line:84%
called a law of reverse
effort that operates in this

00:55:47.244 --> 00:55:48.779 align:middle line:84%
which it's just the
way of saying

00:55:48.779 --> 00:55:52.616 align:middle line:84%
that the harder you try the
more you're going to fail.

00:55:52.616 --> 00:55:58.889 align:middle line:84%
And the key recognition is
that were already connected.

00:55:58.889 --> 00:56:01.258 align:middle line:84%
And so this is not something
you'd have to manipulate

00:56:01.258 --> 00:56:03.894 align:middle line:84%
and control as if
you could anyway.

00:56:03.894 --> 00:56:06.997 align:middle line:84%
It's just a manifestation
of who we are.

00:56:06.997 --> 00:56:12.169 align:middle line:84%
And if we learn to sit down,
be quiet, and stop the chatter,

00:56:12.169 --> 00:56:15.405 align:middle line:84%
most people find that they
can live into an awareness

00:56:15.405 --> 00:56:16.440 align:middle line:90%
of their connectedness

00:56:16.440 --> 00:56:18.975 align:middle line:84%
with other things
and other creatures.

00:56:18.975 --> 00:56:22.746 align:middle line:84%
So although there are ways that
had been recommended about how

00:56:22.746 --> 00:56:26.116 align:middle line:84%
to access this state, we always
have to keep that in mind.

00:56:26.116 --> 00:56:28.084 align:middle line:84%
You know you can
make this happen.

00:56:28.084 --> 00:56:31.254 align:middle line:84%
It's like we talked about
on premonitions once.

00:56:31.254 --> 00:56:33.256 align:middle line:90%
It sort of does you.

00:56:33.256 --> 00:56:35.091 align:middle line:90%
You know you don't do me up.

00:56:35.091 --> 00:56:37.427 align:middle line:84%
But what we need to
do is to find a way

00:56:37.427 --> 00:56:41.331 align:middle line:84%
of inviting this recognition
of unity and oneness

00:56:41.331 --> 00:56:45.435 align:middle line:84%
into our life not that
we can make it happen.

00:56:45.435 --> 00:56:47.604 align:middle line:84%
And so throughout history
there are time-honored ways

00:56:47.604 --> 00:56:48.972 align:middle line:90%
of doing this.

00:56:48.972 --> 00:56:52.609 align:middle line:84%
One of the great ways is just
meditation whether you call

00:56:52.609 --> 00:56:56.913 align:middle line:84%
that contemplation or just
getting quiet or doing nothing.

00:56:56.913 --> 00:57:00.984 align:middle line:84%
All of these methods have a way
of quieting the conscious mind

00:57:00.984 --> 00:57:04.821 align:middle line:84%
so that a deeper way of knowing
and understanding can percolate

00:57:04.821 --> 00:57:07.791 align:middle line:84%
up from their own conscious
and this play itself

00:57:07.791 --> 00:57:09.793 align:middle line:90%
to our conscious awareness.

00:57:09.793 --> 00:57:16.066 align:middle line:84%
There are other ways that have
traditionally been described.

00:57:16.066 --> 00:57:19.336 align:middle line:84%
Many people find that
exposure to nature is a way

00:57:19.336 --> 00:57:25.675 align:middle line:84%
of quieting the aware mind
and listening to classical,

00:57:25.675 --> 00:57:29.646 align:middle line:84%
great music or any kind
of music for that matter.

00:57:29.646 --> 00:57:35.385 align:middle line:84%
Viewing great art in museums
is often described as a way

00:57:35.385 --> 00:57:39.723 align:middle line:84%
of having an epiphany that
helps you understand the reality

00:57:39.723 --> 00:57:41.858 align:middle line:90%
of the unity and oneness.

00:57:41.858 --> 00:57:42.926 align:middle line:90%
Some of these things are

00:57:42.926 --> 00:57:45.562 align:middle line:84%
so ordinary they
are almost comical.

00:57:45.562 --> 00:57:48.098 align:middle line:84%
I have a friend who said that
he had his great awakening

00:57:48.098 --> 00:57:51.468 align:middle line:84%
to the oneness of all things
when one morning he woke up

00:57:51.468 --> 00:57:52.702 align:middle line:90%
and was sitting on the side

00:57:52.702 --> 00:57:55.672 align:middle line:84%
of his bed picking
lint from his navel.

00:57:55.672 --> 00:57:57.274 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Literally?

00:57:57.274 --> 00:57:58.608 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Literally.

00:57:58.608 --> 00:58:02.746 align:middle line:84%
So I don't recommend this
technique but it's part of the--

00:58:02.746 --> 00:58:05.081 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Yes, I mean each
person has an access point.

00:58:05.081 --> 00:58:07.517 align:middle line:84%
Some people have that when
they're taking showers.

00:58:07.517 --> 00:58:09.920 align:middle line:90%
Water seems to be a great mover.

00:58:09.920 --> 00:58:13.123 align:middle line:84%
Another friend of mine whose
high intuitive has her visions

00:58:13.123 --> 00:58:14.224 align:middle line:90%
while she's washing dishes

00:58:14.224 --> 00:58:15.892 align:middle line:84%
with the water running
over her hands.

00:58:15.892 --> 00:58:20.630 align:middle line:84%
And it's just kind of a mind
numbing, blank type of chore.

00:58:20.630 --> 00:58:23.967 align:middle line:84%
But something in that allows the
visions to come through clearly.

00:58:23.967 --> 00:58:25.101 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: Absolutely.

00:58:25.101 --> 00:58:29.172 align:middle line:84%
And as to creativity
the science literature--

00:58:29.172 --> 00:58:33.343 align:middle line:84%
Literature of Discovery
is full of great scientist

00:58:33.343 --> 00:58:36.012 align:middle line:84%
who had their epiphanies
and awakenings

00:58:36.012 --> 00:58:41.618 align:middle line:84%
of the breakthrough while they
were dreaming or during reverie.

00:58:41.618 --> 00:58:44.554 align:middle line:84%
One of the great examples is
Kekule who was sitting in front

00:58:44.554 --> 00:58:48.992 align:middle line:84%
of a fire and was dosing
and he saw the structure

00:58:48.992 --> 00:58:51.795 align:middle line:84%
of the Benzene molecule which
he had not been able to figure

00:58:51.795 --> 00:58:56.299 align:middle line:84%
out because in his dream or
his reverie he saw snake--

00:58:56.299 --> 00:59:00.470 align:middle line:84%
a snake with its tail it
its mouth and discovered

00:59:00.470 --> 00:59:04.407 align:middle line:84%
through this revelation
that the structure was a--

00:59:04.407 --> 00:59:06.142 align:middle line:90%
was a ring compound.

00:59:06.142 --> 00:59:10.814 align:middle line:84%
It totally kick started the
science of organic chemistry.

00:59:10.814 --> 00:59:12.616 align:middle line:90%
We could make a long list of--

00:59:12.616 --> 00:59:13.383 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yes.

00:59:13.383 --> 00:59:14.718 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: So that's our--

00:59:14.718 --> 00:59:15.685 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: There been books
written on that exact thing.

00:59:15.685 --> 00:59:16.286 align:middle line:90%
>> Dossey: There have.

00:59:16.286 --> 00:59:17.687 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:59:17.687 --> 00:59:18.955 align:middle line:84%
>> Dossey: And-- and one of the
threads that runs through all

00:59:18.955 --> 00:59:22.592 align:middle line:84%
